04513nam a22005895i 9780822382409DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223824097 a10.1515/97808223824092doi  a(DE-B1597)552516  a(OCoLC)1097130765  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR3591b.C33 1995 7aPOE0050202bisacsh04a821/.42201 aCable, Lana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCarnal Rhetoric :bMilton's Iconoclasm and the Poetics of Desire /cLana Cable. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Metaphor and "Meaning": Toward a Theory of Creative Iconoclasm -- t2. "Shuffling up such a God": The Rhetorical Agon of Milton's Antiprelatical Tracts -- t3. "Was she thy God?": The Coupling Rhetoric of the Divorce Tracts -- t4. "The image of God in the eye": Areopagitica's Truth -- t5. "Unimprisonable utterance": Itnagination and the Attack on Eikon Basilike -- t6. Samson's Transformative Desire -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, New Historicists have situated the iconoclasm of Milton's poetry and prose within the context of political, cultural, and philosophical discourses that foreshadow early modernism. In Carnal Rhetoric, Lana Cable carries these investigations further by exploring the iconoclastic impulse in Milton's works through detailed analyses of his use of metaphor. Building on a provocative iconoclastic theory of metaphor, she breaks new ground in the area of affective stylistics, not only as it pertains to the writings of Milton but also to all expressive language.Cable traces the development of Milton's iconoclastic poetics from its roots in the antiprelatical tracts, through the divorce tracts and Areopagitica, to its fullest dramatic representation in Eikonoklastes and Samson Agonistes. Arguing that, like every creative act, metaphor is by nature a radical and self-transgressing agent of change, she explores the site where metaphoric language and imaginative desire merge. Examining the demands Milton places on metaphor, particularly his emphasis on language as a vehicle for mortal redemption, Cable demonstrates the ways in which metaphor acts for him as that creative and radical agent of change. In the process, she reveals Milton's engagement, at the deepest levels of linguistic creativity, with the early modern commitment to an imaginative and historic remaking of the world.An insightful and synthetic book, Carnal Rhetoric will appeal to scholars of English literature, Milton, and the Renaissance, as well as to those with an interest in the theory of affective stylistics as it pertains to reader-response criticism, semantics, epistemology, and the philosophy and psychology of language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDesire in literature. 0aEnglish languageyEarly modern, 1500-1700xRhetoric. 0aIconoclasm in literature. 0aMetaphor. 0aModernism (Literature)zEngland. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy17th century. 7aPOETRY / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382409zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382409423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382409.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles